text: "You win by winning."

Forgot which WW1 general said it, apparently it was Field Marshal Sir Douglas Haig, but only demoralized soldiers get trench foot. Units in the worst of conditions with constant rain and mud for days do not suffer bootrot if their morale stays high. Demoralization rots your feet.

I think on the personal plane one can find some examples of how e.g. you may get a cold or a relapse of some chronic condition after suffering a personal defeat or low morale. And high discipline and high morale can keep you alive and well through very brutal physical conditions.

It has more logical explanations too, like units with defeatist attitudes neglecting hygiene protocols due to poor discipline, but a sense of defeat does also directly suppress your immunity. You could spot the demoralized battalions just from the high cases of trench foot alone.

Only tangentially related, but I find it very admirable that there are surgeons who hyperspecialize in one particular procedure and travel around the world to perform it everywhere. Here is Dr. Henry Marsh who pioneered "awake craniotomy" in Albania to operate on some bricklayer.

Leibniz was said to have a very large head, but when they exhumed his supposed skull, it was quite a bit below the average for the time and the chief investigator said he doubted it was really him. In South America they take the hands from graves instead, e.g. Peron, Evita, Che.

"In their book Second Death: Licio Gelli, The P2 Masonic Lodge and The Plot to Destroy Juan Peron [...] write that the Masonic lodge P2, also known as the Propaganda Due, were involved in the theft, and that there was a ritual involved in the cutting of Peron's hands"
